review_comments:
['Insertion detection currently requires `change.rangeLength === 1`, which will miss pasting a full token into an empty editor (typical paste has `rangeLength === 0`). If the goal is to support pasting full tokens, consider also treating multi-character inserts with `rangeLength === 0` as candidate token insertions (while still avoiding single-character typing).

This issue also appears on line 471 of the same file.', "Tests cover replacement-style insertion (rangeLength=1) but not the paste scenario mentioned in the PR description (rangeLength=0, multi-character insert into empty input). Adding a test that simulates paste insertion (e.g. edit range (1,1)-(1,1) with text '@workspace ') would guard the intended behavior and prevent regressions in the insertion heuristic.
```suggestion

	test('deletes pasted token on immediate backspace', () => {
		withTestCodeEditor('', {}, editor => {
			let refreshCount = 0;
			const store = new DisposableStore();
			try {
				const widget = createWidget(editor, () => {
					refreshCount++;
				});
				const ChatTokenDeleterCtor = getChatTokenDeleterCtor();
				store.add(new ChatTokenDeleterCtor(widget));

				editor.executeEdits('test', [{ range: new Range(1, 1, 1, 1), text: '@workspace ' }]);
				assert.strictEqual(editor.getValue(), '@workspace ');

				editor.executeEdits('test', [{ range: new Range(1, 11, 1, 12), text: '' }]);
				assert.strictEqual(editor.getValue(), '');
				assert.strictEqual(refreshCount, 1);
			} finally {
				store.dispose();
			}
		});
	});
```", 'The comment for `variableReg` uses an `@response:2` example, but this regex matches `#...` variables (and the leader is `#`). Updating the example to `#response:2` would avoid confusion.
```suggestion
export const variableReg = /^#([\w_\-]+)(:\d+)?(?=(\s|$|\b))/i; // A #-variable with an optional numeric : arg (#response:2)
```', "## Pull request overview

This PR updates the chat input editor’s backspace handling so that when a slash/agent/variable token is inserted as a whole (e.g., via completion), an immediate backspace removes the entire inserted token rather than a single character.

**Changes:**
- Reworked `ChatTokenDeleter` to track the last inserted token range and delete it on the next matching backspace.
- Exported `agentReg` and `variableReg` from the request parser so the editor contrib can reuse the same token-detection regexes.
- Added a new browser unit test suite to validate token deletion behavior and non-deletion cases.

### Reviewed changes

Copilot reviewed 3 out of 3 changed files in this pull request and generated 3 comments.

| File | Description |
| ---- | ----------- |
| `src/vs/workbench/contrib/chat/test/browser/widget/input/editor/chatInputEditorContrib.test.ts` | Adds coverage for immediate-backspace token deletion and ensures no deletion when editing inside/after insertion. |
| `src/vs/workbench/contrib/chat/common/requestParser/chatRequestParser.ts` | Exposes agent/variable regexes for reuse by UI logic. |
| `src/vs/workbench/contrib/chat/browser/widget/input/editor/chatInputEditorContrib.ts` | Implements the new “previous inserted token” deletion heuristic in `ChatTokenDeleter`. |


<details>
<summary>Comments suppressed due to low confidence (1)</summary>

**src/vs/workbench/contrib/chat/browser/widget/input/editor/chatInputEditorContrib.ts:476**
* The delete-path can re-trigger itself because `executeEdits` inside `onDidChangeModelContent` will emit another content-change event while `prevInsertTokenRange` is still set. Also, the current condition will treat any deletion whose `endColumn` matches as a token-delete (including selection deletes).

Consider tightening the condition to only match a single-character backspace at the end of the token (e.g. `change.rangeLength === 1` and `change.range.startColumn === prevInsertTokenRange.endColumn - 1`), and clear `prevInsertTokenRange` before calling `executeEdits` to avoid re-entrancy.
```
					this.widget.inputEditor.executeEdits(this.id, [{
						range: prevInsertTokenRange,
						text: '',
					}]);
					this.widget.refreshParsedInput();
				}
```
</details>

"]

